  }
}

const app = new Controller(new Model(), new View());
```

In this example, we create the Model, View, and Controller classes. The Model class stores the data and has methods to add and retrieve data. The View class handles rendering to the screen. The Controller class sets up event listeners, handles user actions, updates the model and view, and initializes the application.

The Controller constructor takes instances of the Model and View classes, sets up the form listener, renders the initial data, and binds the addItem method to the controller's "this" value.

The addItem method is modified to use "this" to refer to the controller's instance. When the user submits a new item through the form, the method adds the item to the model, updates the view, and clears the input field.

Finally, we create a new instance of the Controller class and pass in instances of the Model and View classes.

